## Digital Twin → Graph Chat: natural-language chat with the knowledge graph

Context: The MCP server already exposes knowledge-graph tools
(`list_entity_types`, `describe_entity`, `get_graphql_schema`,
`query_graphql`, `get_status`) that any LLM client (Cursor, Claude
Desktop, Databricks Playground) can use to converse with a Digital
Twin. Power-users of the OntoBricks web UI asked for the same
capability without leaving the app.

This change adds a new **Graph Chat** entry under Digital Twin →
Navigation. The chatbot calls the same external REST surface as the
MCP server (`/api/v1/digitaltwin/...`, `/graphql/{domain}`) plus the
internal SPARQL executor (`/dtwin/execute`) and renders the LLM's
reply inline in the panel -- no floating FAB, full-height section.

Changes:

Frontend (menu + UI + assets):
1. src/front/config/menu_config.json — new `chat` item (label
   "Graph Chat", icon `bi-chat-dots`) inserted after `graphql` under
   Digital Twin → Data/Navigation.
2. src/front/templates/partials/dtwin/_query_chat.html (NEW) — section
   header with domain / graph badges and a "Switch domain" button,
   the `.graph-chat-container` wrapper (messages + suggestions +
   textarea + send + clear). Re-uses the `.assistant-*` class family.
3. src/front/templates/dtwin.html — new `#chat-section` sidebar panel
   that includes the partial, plus `<link>` + `<script defer>` tags
   for the new CSS/JS.
4. src/front/static/query/css/query-chat.css (NEW) — full-height
   layout and spacing that inlines the chat inside the panel instead
   of anchoring it above a FAB.
5. src/front/static/query/js/query-chat.js (NEW) — embedded chat
   controller (no drag/FAB). Captures `sidebarSectionChanged` to
   lazy-init on first show. Posts `{message, history}` to
   `/dtwin/assistant/chat`, renders the reply as Markdown, exposes a
   collapsible "Tools used" trace, and supports Enter / Shift+Enter
   + Clear chat.

Backend (agent + context + endpoint):
6. src/agents/tools/context.py — extended `ToolContext` with four
   Graph-Chat-only fields: `dtwin_base_url`, `dtwin_session_cookies`,
   `dtwin_registry_params`, `dtwin_domain_name`.
7. src/agents/tools/graph_formatting.py (NEW) — shared formatting
   helpers (`local_name`, `pretty_predicate`, `format_find_response`,
   `format_graphql_response`, `format_sparql_rows`) extracted from
   the MCP server logic so the new agent renders identical
   LLM-friendly text. The MCP server is left untouched because it is
   packaged as a standalone wheel without `agents/` on its path.
8. src/agents/agent_dtwin_chat/__init__.py (NEW) — re-exports
   `run_agent` and `AgentResult`.
9. src/agents/agent_dtwin_chat/tools.py (NEW) — six tools:
   - `list_entity_types` → GET /api/v1/digitaltwin/stats
   - `describe_entity`   → GET /api/v1/digitaltwin/triples/find
   - `get_status`        → GET /api/v1/digitaltwin/status
   - `get_graphql_schema`→ GET /graphql/{domain}/schema
   - `query_graphql`     → POST /graphql/{domain}
   - `run_sparql`        → POST /dtwin/execute (internal route; same
     session cookie forwarded; mutating SPARQL keywords -- DROP,
     DELETE, INSERT, CREATE, CLEAR, LOAD, COPY, MOVE, ADD -- are
     rejected client-side).
   Every call uses a loopback `httpx.Client` bound to
   `dtwin_base_url` with the user's session cookies.
10. src/agents/agent_dtwin_chat/engine.py (NEW) — clone of the
    ontology-assistant engine: same `MAX_ITERATIONS=12`, same
    `call_serving_endpoint` / `dispatch_tool` / `accumulate_usage`
    helpers from `engine_base`, same `@trace_agent` span. Ships its
    own `SYSTEM_PROMPT` describing the knowledge-graph tools and the
    "domain is pre-selected" contract so the LLM never tries to
    list/select domains.
11. src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py — new `POST /dtwin/assistant/chat`.
    Resolves domain + registry (`DigitalTwin.resolve_registry`),
    reads the LLM endpoint via `require_serving_llm`, computes the
    loopback base URL (`DATABRICKS_APP_PORT`/`PORT`/8000), forwards
    the caller's session cookies to the agent, runs
    `agent_dtwin_chat.run_agent` off-thread, and returns
    `{success, reply, tools[], iterations, usage}`.

