## Code review hardening: layering, error handling, dedup, class-first

Follow-up to the `full_rules` code review that inventoried 1475 tests
plus audit findings across logging, error handling, layering, class-first
policy, duplication, and dead code. Implements the safe, low-risk subset
(items A–J). All 1491 tests pass (up from 1475: `networkx` venv refresh
restored `tests/test_community_detector.py`).

Layering (rule §2.2: HTML routes serve pages only, JSON lives under
`api/routers/internal/`):
- Moved `src/front/routes/help.py` → `src/api/routers/internal/help.py`.
  The file was 100% JSON/binary endpoints (`/api/help/docs`,
  `/api/help/docs/{slug}`, `/api/help/docs/images/{name}`,
  `/api/help/docs/screenshots/{name}`) — no `TemplateResponse` ever.
  URL paths are unchanged, so `front/static/global/js/help-docs.js`
  keeps working.
- Updated `_docs_dir()` to account for the new depth
  (`src/api/routers/internal/` → four `dirname` hops to repo root).
- Registered the router in `api/routers/internal/__init__.py` and
  removed it from `front/routes/__init__.py`.

Error handling (rule §7: never leak `str(e)` to clients, never
log-and-swallow):
- `src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py` — the "ontology is empty"
  branch of the GraphQL schema endpoint now raises `ValidationError`
  instead of returning `{"success": False, ...}`, matching the
  sibling error path two lines below.
- `src/back/core/w3c/shacl/SHACLService.py` — `run_inference` and
  `validate_graph` no longer put `str(exc)` into the `error` /
  `report_text` fields returned to clients; they log with
  `exc_info=True` and expose a generic, sanitized message.
- `src/back/core/databricks/DashboardService.py.get_dashboard_parameters`
  — replaces `{"error": str(exc)}` with a generic message; HTTP
  errors report only the status code to callers.
- `src/back/core/triplestore/TripleStoreBackend.py` — `transitive_closure`
  and `symmetric_expand` now log failures at WARNING with
  `exc_info=True` instead of silently swallowing at DEBUG level; the
  fallback-to-empty-list behaviour is preserved for callers that
  expect a best-effort result.
- `src/agents/tools/sql.py` — added `exc_info=True` on the SQL tool
  error log. `str(exc)` is kept in the tool output by design: agent
  tools must surface the error text to the LLM so it can retry.

Class-first (rule §10.1 / §10.3: one public class per file named
after the class; no loose module-level state):
- `src/back/objects/registry/service.py` →
  `src/back/objects/registry/RegistryService.py`.
- `src/back/objects/registry/permissions.py` →
  `src/back/objects/registry/PermissionService.py`.
- Updated every internal import that bypassed the package re-exports
  (`scheduler.py`, `session/DomainSession.py`, `agents/tools/documents.py`),
  plus the `mock.patch` target strings in `tests/test_permissions.py`
  and the Cursor rules example in `.cursor/07-project-conventions.mdc`.
- `src/back/objects/domain/version_status.py` — wrapped the TTL cache
  in a `VersionStatusCache` class with `get` / `set` / `clear` /
  `snapshot` methods. The four module-level helpers now delegate to
  a singleton so the existing `back.objects.domain` public surface
  is unchanged; the private `_version_status_cache` dict is still
  exported as an alias to the class store for the expiration
  simulation in `tests/test_version_status_cache.py`.

Duplication / Extract Function:
- `src/back/objects/session/DomainSession.py` — extracted
  `_sanitized_ontology_for_hash()` and `_sha256_json()` so
  `_config_snapshot()` and `_split_snapshots()` no longer copy-paste
  the ontology sanitation + JSON-sort-SHA routine. Promoted the
  local `import copy, hashlib, json` out of the method bodies into
  the module imports.
- `src/agents/tools/graph_formatting.py` — `local_name()` now
  delegates to `back.core.w3c.rdf_utils.uri_local_name` and adds a
  single fallback line so the formatter still renders the raw URI
  (instead of an empty string) when the URI ends in a bare `#` or
  `/`. The MCP sidecar (`src/mcp-server/server/app.py`) keeps its
  own copy intentionally — it ships as an independent wheel with
  only `server/` on its Python path (see docstring).

Deps / environment:
- `pyproject.toml` already declares `networkx>=3.0`; no change
  needed. Refreshing the local venv with `uv pip install networkx`
  restores `tests/test_community_detector.py` collection (16 tests).

Evaluated but deliberately not changed (risk outweighs the benefit):
- `back.core.reasoning.SPARQLRuleEngine._resolve_term` vs.
  `back.core.w3c.sparql.SparqlTranslator._resolve_term` — superficial
  similarity only; the two helpers take different parameter shapes
  (`(term, prefixes)` vs. `(term, base_uri, uri_map)`), use different
  namespace sources, and have different fallbacks for unresolved
  names. Extracting a shared core would either bloat the signature or
  break one of the two behaviours.
- `api/routers/internal/ontology.py` `/swrl/validate` and `/rules/validate`
  returning `{"success": false, "valid": false, "errors": [...]}` —
  kept as-is. These endpoints report validation outcomes, not request
  failures; the structured `errors` payload is the useful return value
  and is the documented contract for the client-side validator UI.
- `api/routers/internal/domain.py` `current_user` returning
  `{"success": false, "email": ""}` when no Databricks client — this
  is a benign "no identity resolvable" fallback consumed by the UI,
  not an error condition.
- `src/mcp-server/server/app.py` logging via `logging.getLogger(__name__)`
  — the MCP server is a standalone Databricks App with its own
  `pyproject.toml` / `requirements.txt` and does not import from
  `back.core.*`; the central `get_logger()` policy only applies to
  the main OntoBricks FastAPI app.

